b'' b"i'm working on an x11r5 application and have concerns regarding" b'standard colormaps.' b'' b'the x11r5 documentation says: "usually, a window manager creates' b'these colormaps." i wonder what window manager the writer had' b'in mind. neither twm or mwm seem to create standard colormaps.' b'' b'of course, one can use xstdcmap to create standard colormaps.' b"however, xstdcmap doesn't seem to try very hard to avoid" b'conflicts with the default colormap. when i use standard' b'colormaps created by xstdcmap, the rest of my display goes black.' b'so it seems as if use of standard colormaps causes the very' b'problem standard colormaps are intended to avoid. perhaps' b'if every application used standard colormaps, things would' b'be wonderful. but not many applications seem to use' b'standard colormaps.' b'' b'finally, the operation of the functions xmugetcolormapallocation,' b'xmustandardcolormap, and xmucreatecolormap seem inconsistent' b'with the section of the x11r5 xlib documentation.' b'' b'according to the section of the x11r5 xlib documentation (p. b'' b'for grayscale colormaps, only the colormap, red_max, red_mult, and' b'base_pixel members are defined. the other members are ignored.' b'to compute a grayscale pixel value, use the following expression:' b'' b'(gray red_mult base_pixel) &0xffffffff' b'' b'xmugetcolormapallocation, defined in mit/lib/xmu/cmapalloc.c, is' b'used by xmulookupstandardcolormap, defined in mit/lib/xmu/lookupcmap.c' b'to select red_max, green_max, and blue_max values for the' b'call to xmustandardcolormap. when the rgb_gray_map property is' b'specified, xmugetcolormapallocation sets red_max to of the' b'total number of cells in the gray scale, sets green_max to b'of the total number, and sets blue_max ot of the total number.' b'referring to section one would expect xmugetcolormapallocation' b'to set red_max to the total number of cells in the gray scale.' b'' b'when the rgb_gray_map property is specified, xmustandardcolormap,' b'